        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is cost of goods sold a debit or a credit?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Cost of goods sold is a debit, because it is an expense that reduces profit. When goods costing Rs 2 lakh are sold, the entry debits Cost of Goods Sold Rs 2 lakh and credits Inventory Rs 2 lakh. It carries a credit only when a sale is reversed or stock is returned, which pushes the balance back down."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between cost of goods sold and operating expenses?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Cost of goods sold covers costs tied directly to the goods sold, such as raw material, purchase freight and factory labour, while operating expenses cover running the business, such as rent, salaries of office staff and marketing. Gross profit is sales minus cost of goods sold; operating profit is gross profit minus operating expenses, so the split changes both ratios."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does GST form part of cost of goods sold in India?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "GST does not form part of cost of goods sold where input tax credit is available, because the tax is recorded in the input credit ledger and recovered against output GST. Purchases are booked net of GST. Where credit is blocked, for example on goods used for personal consumption, the GST paid is added to purchase cost and does hit cost of goods sold."
          }
        }
      ]
